  "prompt": "If time slows down as you approach the speed of light, then what time scale is light on?",
  "response": "This is an interesting question that touches on some fundamental principles of special relativity. According to Einstein's theory, for a photon (a particle of light) traveling at the speed of light, time effectively stands still. \n\nFrom the perspective of a photon:\n- Time does not pass\n- Distance contracts to zero\n- The photon experiences no time between emission and absorption\n\nThis means that from light's \"perspective,\" its entire journey happens instantaneously. However, this is a bit of a conceptual paradox, as a photon doesn't actually have a frame of reference in the way massive objects do.\n\nFor an outside observer, light always travels at a constant speed (c) and takes a measurable amount of time to traverse distances. But for the light itself, if we try to apply the concept of time, it would be frozen or non-existent.\n\nThis peculiar nature of light is one of the many counterintuitive aspects of relativity that challenge our everyday understanding of space and time.",
